Prologue
"Please, I beg you!" Queen Eirwen pleaded, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had only fathered sons up until this point.
"You have two choices: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did.
Frostfell had not always been a single kingdom. Previously, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and an endless war broke out between the two kingdoms, until finally the South offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was ready for anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she was to bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North would unite with the South to form a kingdom. The North accepted the offer and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
„I beg you, my king, do with me what you will, lock me up, banish me or kill me, but spare my child，“ pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen full of contempt. Perhaps, but only perhaps, he would have mercy on her. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and had given him his sons.
„Alright. The child can stay in the palace，“ he said, which the queen acknowledged with a sigh. „But，“ he added, „you will be executed.“
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly she turned her gaze to the floor. „Yes, my king.“ She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's free rooms. Afterwards, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution ground, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution ground, a loud uproar broke out among the citizens when they realized that their only beloved queen was to be executed. Some people cried, others shouted and attacked the guards. Others still wondered why this should happen, but everyone agreed.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they doing this to her?”
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
„Don't give up, Kari.“ This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knocking sound could be heard from the room located all the way to the left in the south wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was in that room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors spread among the maids. Allegedly, the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and was waiting to be let out.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory and walked towards the south wing, while the servants went about their business and whispered among themselves. They had no idea what was hidden behind the door.
The rumors naturally involved Ivory as well, since Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory in front of the beautifully decorated door with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last attempt, actual entry would be granted this time. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory laughed at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock could be heard from inside, probably to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. In the past, Ivory had walked in without asking.
Ivory heard a knock from inside. That probably meant a "Yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from a supposedly empty room, although Ivory had been going in there for several years now.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. Paper was everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. Also, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her bedsheet, and was reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is that?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
